{{for|the American guitarist|Todd May (guitarist)}} {{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st-century philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Todd Gifford May''' |birth_date = 1955 |birth_place =[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Continental philosophy|Continental]] | institutions = [[Clemson University]] |main_interests = [[political philosophy]] |notable_ideas = [[post-structuralist anarchism]] | spouse = | education = | alma_mater = [[Penn State University]] |influences = [[Gilles Deleuze]], [[Jacques Ranciere]] |influenced = |awards = }}
'''Todd Gifford May'''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://media.clemson.edu/caah/upload/files/386.CV.2016.03.18.9.52.28.pdf |title=Curriculum Vitae |publisher= Clemson University }}</ref> (born 1955 in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]) is a [[political philosophy|political philosopher]] who writes on topics of [[anarchism]], [[poststructuralism]], and [[post-structuralist anarchism]]. He is currently Class of 1941 Memorial Professor of Philosophy at [[Clemson University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.believermag.com/exclusives/?read=interview_may |title=Todd May |first=Matt |last=Bieber |work= The Believer}}</ref>
==Career== Art academic [[Allan Antliff]] described May's 1994 ''The Political Philosophy of Poststructuralist Anarchism'' as "seminal", and credited the book with introducing "post-structuralist anarchism", later abbreviated as "[[post-anarchism]]".<ref>{{cite journal |jstor=25195125|title=Anarchy, Power, and Poststructuralism |first=Allan|last= Antliff|journal=SubStance|volume= 36| issue = 2, issue 113: The Future of Anarchism |date=2007|pages= 56–66 }}</ref> May has published works on major [[poststructuralist]] philosophers, including [[Gilles Deleuze]] and [[Michel Foucault]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Gilles Deleuze: An Introduction |url=http://ndpr.nd.edu/news/gilles-deleuze-an-introduction/ |journal=Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews |date= June 2005|publisher=Notre Dame University}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00131940802225119?journalCode=heds20 |title=A Review of "Philosophy of Foucault (European Philosophy Series)|author=Anthony A. Defalco|pages= 77–82 | date= 14 August 2008|doi= 10.1080/00131940802225119 }}</ref> He also wrote books on more general topics accessible to the general reader, including ''Death'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/809ced06-9e6b-11de-b0aa-00144feabdc0 |title=Better late than never |work=Financial Times |first=Stephen |last=Cave|date=September 12, 2009 }}</ref> ''Our Practices, Our Selves, or, What It Means to Be Human'',<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Dialogue: Canadian Philosophical Review |volume= 42|issue =1 |pages= 150–153 |title=Our Practices, Our Selves, or, What It Means to Be Human|doi=10.1017/S0012217300004273|first=Réal |last=Fillion |date=April 1, 2010}}</ref> ''Friendship in an Age of Economics: Resisting the Forces of Neoliberalism'',<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.ephemerajournal.org/contribution/friendship-and-counter-conduct-neoliberal-regime-truth |title=Friendship and counter-conduct in the neoliberal regime of truth |journal=Ephemera |volume= 13|issue=3|pages= 683–693|first=Richard|last= Weiskopf }}</ref> ''A Significant Life: Human Meaning in a Silent Universe'',<ref>{{cite journal |url =http://ndpr.nd.edu/news/a-significant-life-human-meaning-in-a-silent-universe/ |title=A Significant Life: Human Meaning in a Silent Universe |first= Thaddeus|last= Metz |journal=Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews |date= 19 August 2015|publisher=Notre Dame University}}</ref> ''A Fragile Life: Accepting Our Vulnerability''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/matters-large-and-small-reading-todd-mays-a-fragile-life-in-the-wake-of-hurricane-harvey/|title=Matters Large and Small: Reading Todd May’s "A Fragile Life" in the Wake of Hurricane Harvey|first= Robert |last=Zaretsky|work= Los Angeles Reviews of Books |date=October 10, 2017 }}</ref>
May is also the philosophical advisor to the NBC television show ''[[The Good Place]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Philosophy on TV: "The Good Place"|url=https://blog.apaonline.org/2017/06/21/philosophy-on-tv-the-good-place/|website=Blog of the APA|accessdate=11 January 2018|date=21 June 2017}}</ref>
